I want to create a SmartContract method, that consume and verify specified proof.

Reading over other examples, I understood that this is possible by specifying the proof class in the method args (this bakes in the program's verification key inside the smart contract's verification key), i.e. 
`class MyProgram extends Experimental.ZkProgram.Proof(myProgram) {}`
`@method verifyProof(proof: MyProgram) { proof.verify() }`

But it does not seem to work in the example below. What am I doing wrong?

```js
import {
  Field,
  Bool,
  method,
  Experimental,
  SmartContract,
  PrivateKey,
  Provable,
} from 'o1js';

const myProgram = Experimental.ZkProgram({
  publicOutput: Field,
  methods: {
    prove: {
      privateInputs: [ Field ],
      method(value: Field): Field {
        value.assertEquals(Field(1))
        return Field(1);
      },
    },
  },
});

class MyProgram extends Experimental.ZkProgram.Proof(myProgram) {}

const otherProgram = Experimental.ZkProgram({
  publicOutput: Field,
  methods: {
    prove: {
      privateInputs: [ Field ],
      method(value: Field): Field {
        value.assertEquals(Field(2))
        return Field(2);
      },
    },
  },
});


export class Contract extends SmartContract {
  @method verifyProof(proof: MyProgram) {
    proof.verify()
    Provable.log(proof, Bool(true))
  }
}

// create proofs
await myProgram.compile()
await otherProgram.compile()

const proof = await myProgram.prove(Field(1))
const otherProof = await otherProgram.prove(Field(2))
console.log(proof, otherProof)

// use proofs inside the SmartContract method
const zkAppPrivateKey = PrivateKey.random();
const zkAppAddress = zkAppPrivateKey.toPublicKey();
const zkApp = new Contract(zkAppAddress);

await zkApp.verifyProof(proof);
await zkApp.verifyProof(otherProof);
```

Am I again missing something trivial..? 🤔  Expanded the example by creating transactions and proving them.  Proving did not fail.

